@page "/publish-guide"

<PageTitle>Publish Blazor WASM on GitHub Pages</PageTitle>

<h1>Publish Blazor WebAssembly on GitHub Pages</h1>

<p class="lead">
    This sample project is configured to deploy automatically to GitHub Pages.
    Follow the steps below to use the same setup in your own repository.
</p>

<section class="guide-section">
    <h2>Prerequisites</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>.NET SDK (this project uses <strong>.NET 10</strong>)</li>
        <li>A GitHub repository (public repos get free GitHub Pages)</li>
        <li>Your default branch pushed to GitHub (usually <code>main</code>)</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="guide-section">
    <h2>1. Create the Blazor WASM project</h2>
    <pre><code>dotnet new blazorwasm -o BlazorGitHubPagesDemo
cd BlazorGitHubPagesDemo</code></pre>
    <p>
        Keep <code>&lt;base href="/" /&gt;</code> in <code>wwwroot/index.html</code> for local development.
        The workflow rewrites it at publish time to match your repository name.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="guide-section">
    <h2>2. Add the GitHub Actions workflow</h2>
    <p>Create <code>.github/workflows/dotnet.yaml</code> with content like this:</p>
    <pre><code>name: DeployBlazorWebAssembly

on:
  push:
    branches: [ "main" ]

jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
    - uses: actions/checkout@v4

    - name: Setup .NET
      uses: actions/setup-dotnet@v4
      with:
        dotnet-version: 10.0.x

    - name: Publish Blazor WebAssembly project
      run: dotnet publish BlazorGitHubPagesDemo.csproj -c Release -o release --nologo

    - name: Change base-tag in index.html from / to BlazorGitHubPagesDemo
      run: sed -i 's/&lt;base href="\/" \/&gt;/&lt;base href="\/BlazorGitHubPagesDemo\/" \/&gt;/g' release/wwwroot/index.html

    - name: Add 404.html (for GitHub Pages SPA fallback)
      run: cp release/wwwroot/index.html release/wwwroot/404.html

    - name: Add .nojekyll file
      run: touch release/wwwroot/.nojekyll

    - name: Deploy to GitHub Pages
      uses: JamesIves/github-pages-deploy-action@4.1.5
      with:
        token: $@@{{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}
        branch: gh-pages
        folder: release/wwwroot</code></pre>

    <h3>Customize for your repository</h3>
    <table class="table table-sm">
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>What to change</th>
                <th>Where</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td>Default branch name</td>
                <td><code>on.push.branches</code> (use <code>master</code> if that is your default)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>.NET version</td>
                <td><code>dotnet-version</code> in the Setup .NET step</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Project file name</td>
                <td><code>dotnet publish</code> command</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Repository name (URL path)</td>
                <td>The <code>sed</code> step — replace <code>BlazorGitHubPagesDemo</code> with your repo name</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>
</section>

<section class="guide-section">
    <h2>3. Why these post-publish steps matter</h2>
    <dl>
        <dt><code>&lt;base href&gt;</code></dt>
        <dd>
            GitHub Pages serves project sites at <code>https://&lt;user&gt;.github.io/&lt;repo&gt;/</code>.
            Blazor needs the base path to load scripts and assets from the correct URL.
        </dd>
        <dt><code>404.html</code></dt>
        <dd>
            A copy of <code>index.html</code> so deep links (for example <code>/counter</code>) reload correctly
            instead of returning a GitHub 404 page.
        </dd>
        <dt><code>.nojekyll</code></dt>
        <dd>
            Tells GitHub Pages not to ignore folders starting with <code>_</code>, which Blazor uses
            (for example <code>_framework</code>).
        </dd>
    </dl>
</section>

<section class="guide-section">
    <h2>4. Configure GitHub</h2>
    <ol>
        <li>Push your code to GitHub.</li>
        <li>
            Open <strong>Settings → Actions → General</strong> and set
            <strong>Workflow permissions</strong> to <em>Read and write permissions</em>.
        </li>
        <li>
            Open <strong>Settings → Pages</strong>. Under <strong>Build and deployment</strong>,
            set <strong>Source</strong> to <em>Deploy from a branch</em> and choose the
            <code>gh-pages</code> branch (created by the workflow after the first successful run).
        </li>
        <li>
            Wait for the <strong>Actions</strong> tab to show a green check on
            <em>DeployBlazorWebAssembly</em>, then open
            <code>https://&lt;username&gt;.github.io/&lt;repository&gt;/</code>.
        </li>
    </ol>
</section>

<section class="guide-section">
    <h2>5. Native WASM workloads (optional)</h2>
    <p>
        If your app uses libraries that require native WASM builds (for example SkiaSharp or SQLite),
        install the workload before publish:
    </p>
    <pre><code>- name: Install .NET WASM Build Tools
  run: dotnet workload install wasm-tools</code></pre>
    <p>Add this step after <em>Setup .NET</em> and before <em>Publish</em>.</p>
</section>

